What Does the Application Layer Do?
1. Provides Network Services
It allows applications to use network resources.
Example:
Web browsing
Email
Video calls
Online games
2. User Authentication
Checks whether a user is allowed to access a service.
Example:
Logging into Gmail
Logging into Instagram
Banking applications
3. File Transfer
Allows sending and receiving files.
Example:
Downloading PDFs
Uploading assignments
Sending files via FTP
4. Email Services
Helps send and receive emails.
Example:
Gmail
Outlook
Yahoo Mail
5. Name Resolution
Converts website names into IP addresses using DNS.
Example:
You type
www.google.com
DNS converts it into something like
142.250.182.14
so your computer knows where to connect.
Common Protocols of Layer 7
Protocol	Purpose
HTTP	Loads websites
HTTPS	Secure websites
FTP	File transfer
SMTP	Sending emails
POP3	Receiving emails
IMAP	Accessing emails
DNS	Converts domain names to IP addresses
Telnet	Remote login (not secure)
SSH	Secure remote login
Real Example (Opening Google)
Suppose you open
https://www.google.com
Here's what happens:
Chrome asks the Application Layer to open Google.
The Application Layer sends a DNS request to find Google's IP address.
After getting the IP address, it sends an HTTPS request.
Google responds with the webpage.
The webpage is displayed in your browser.
In Cybersecurity
The Application Layer is a common target for attacks because it handles user-facing services.
Examples include:
SQL Injection
Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)
Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)
Brute-force login attacks
Phishing websites
Security tools include:
Web Application Firewalls (WAFs)
Authentication systems
CAPTCHA
HTTPS/TLS
Input validation
